		<td><b>Can you stretch scanlines horizontaly?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I've seen some crazy screen effects, in making whatever is on the screen stretched out verticaly. <br /><br />I don't know how to pull this off, ive read somewhere on the vertical aspect that it deals with $2000 or something, but what I'm really curious about, is can this same effect be done on a horizontal bases? Taking the entire image disaplyed, and stretching it horizontaly instead of verticaly?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>lidnariq</b> [ Fri Mar 07, 2014 3:04 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Can you stretch scanlines horizontaly?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Stretching things vertically is a standard raster effect and requires nothing more than the ability to change the scrolling values as the screen is drawn. (vis: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raster_bar" class="postlink">wikipedia:Rasterbars</a>, <a href="http://www.pouet.net/prod.php?which=2048" class="postlink">pouet:Copper by Surprise!</a>).<br /><br />In some instances (e.g. VGA compatible hardware) vertical stretching is additionally a natively supported operation of the hardware, without needing any CPU involvement.<br /><br />Stretching things horizontally requires a little more help from the graphics unit. I doubt the NES provides enough rope.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


